00:03:21.220 --> 00:03:29.069
\b0 So my purpose today is to expand the idea
of accessible technology and to show you the

00:03:29.069 --> 00:03:37.760
way we make our shared world of buildings,
of technologies, of public spaces, practices,

00:03:37.760 --> 00:03:46.249
laws, culture and attitude and how it builds
a total environment which welcomes some people

00:03:46.249 --> 00:03:53.579
and keeps other people out. So the talk is
going to present an evolution of how accessible

00:03:53.579 --> 00:04:01.430
-- technologies in the very broadest sense
make our citizenry more inclusive and diverse.

00:04:01.430 --> 00:04:08.299
So the principle that I'm going to be illustrating
to you today is that accessible technology

00:04:08.299 --> 00:04:12.919
is everywhere once you know how to look for
it. \

00:04:12.919 --> 00:04:18.320
Okay. People with disabilities, of course,
have always use technology to participate

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:24.240
in a world that's not built for them. For
most of history, of course, disabled people

00:04:24.240 --> 00:04:30.250
out in public have been beggars. The figure
of the crippled or the blind beggar accessing

00:04:30.250 --> 00:04:37.610
public space with technology appears often
in such well-known artworks as the ones I'm

00:04:37.610 --> 00:04:46.060
showing you here, the 1525 painting by Pieter
Bruegel or this 1916 photograph of a blind

00:04:46.060 --> 00:04:49.520
beggar by the American photographer Paul Strand.
\

