00:10:12.030 --> 00:10:16.530
\b0 \cf0 Princeton philosopher Peter Singer
advocates that the disable newborns should

00:10:16.530 --> 00:10:23.240
be euthanized on the basis of parental discretion
and there's a quote here by Peter Singer "We

00:10:23.240 --> 00:10:29.870
think that some infants with severe disabilities
should be killed." And he holds to that philosophical

00:10:29.870 --> 00:10:36.470
position to this day. \
Now, for a cheerier topic

00:10:36.470 --> 00:10:40.650
\b [Laughter]
\b0 , what I'm calling inclusive world building

00:10:40.650 --> 00:10:47.040
is a way of thinking which strives to make
a world in which a diverse range of human

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:58.080
beings can use effectively and participate
fully. Inclusive world building is a set of

00:10:58.080 --> 00:11:04.010
legal and material practices born of the civil
and the human rights movement of the mid 20th

00:11:04.010 --> 00:11:10.600
century that changed the composition of the
citizenry who could fully participate in all

00:11:10.600 --> 00:11:18.260
aspects of civil life and some of this legislation
you are aware of is in constant the Americans

00:11:18.260 --> 00:11:25.360
with Disabilities Act of 1990 and 2009 as
well as the worldwide United Nations Treaty

00:11:25.360 --> 00:11:32.480
and the Rights of People with Disabilities
which was enacted in 2008.\

00:11:32.480 --> 00:11:39.390
For the rest of my time today, I'm going to
present you aspects of inclusive world building

00:11:39.390 --> 00:11:45.000
developed and enacted as a direct result of
the legal and the material initiatives that

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:51.370
developed that with the human and civil rights
movement. Inclusive design is a guiding principle

00:11:51.370 --> 00:11:57.950
of world building that has transformed the
built environment by allowing a wide diversity

00:11:57.950 --> 00:12:07.080
of citizens previously excluded to enter in
to and use the world that we have built together

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:14.830
and that we share in order for them to use
and to exercise the privileges and the obligations

00:12:14.830 --> 00:12:22.320
of a democratic citizenship, so inclusive
design. \

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:28.380
What I'm calling inclusive design is a principle
of world making as express through a variety

00:12:28.380 --> 00:12:34.471
of terms some of which you might be familiar
with, inclusive design, design for all, universal

00:12:34.471 --> 00:12:40.580
design, human-centered design, barrier-free
design. One definition that I like to put

00:12:40.580 --> 00:12:48.160
forward that I've developed is inclusive design
is human-centered design of everything with

00:12:48.160 --> 00:12:55.940
everyone in mind and I'm going to try to show
you some examples. I want to take a moment

00:12:55.940 --> 00:13:02.720
to call attention to the Iconography of Inclusive
World Building. As a way to kind of gestured

00:13:02.720 --> 00:13:11.050
to the varying solutions that human communities
have developed to extend the opportunity to

00:13:11.050 --> 00:13:18.970
ex -- previously excluded citizens to participate
in civic life. So the international symbol

00:13:18.970 --> 00:13:28.450
of access I love this because it's both an
icon and a sign as well a material technology

00:13:28.450 --> 00:13:35.680
of accessibility that calls the attention
to the accessible features of the built environment

00:13:35.680 --> 00:13:42.060
that actually tend to go unnoticed because
we routinary use them. So these various icons

00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:48.920
